51:32.423 --> 51:37.127
JUDY WOODRUFF: And speaking of
space, that brings us to our
"NewsHour" Shares of the

51:37.127 --> 51:41.498
day, something that caught our
eye which might be of interest
to you, too.

51:41.498 --> 51:49.473
From Russia to Paris to Las
Vegas, stargazers around the
world were treated to an
uncommon

51:49.473 --> 51:56.413
astronomical event last evening:
a total lunar eclipse that
occurred during a rare so-called

51:56.413 --> 52:03.153
supermoon. The phenomenon
happens when the sun, Earth and
moon perfectly align as the

52:03.153 --> 52:07.858
moon's orbit brings it closest
to Earth. This made the moon
appear bigger and brighter than

52:07.858 --> 52:10.160
usual.

52:10.160 --> 52:15.866
And sunlight refracting around
the Earth bathed it in an eerie
reddish glow, giving it the

52:15.866 --> 52:23.440
name blood moon. This double
feature has not occurred since
1982. And whether or not clouds

52:23.440 --> 52:28.679
obscured your view, you will
have to wait until 2033 to see
it again.

52:28.679 --> 52:31.715
Wow.

